# Notion Coding Workflow

When a user requests a task or starts a coding session, always follow these steps in order:

## Step 1 — Read tasks from Notion

Use the Notion MCP to retrieve the list of tasks with status **"Todo"**:

- Query the database and filter for `Status = Todo`
- Display the list to the user so they can choose which task to work on
- Retrieve the `title` and `description` (if available) of the selected task

## Step 2 — Confirm requirements

Before doing anything, clarify:

- What is the specific goal of the task?
- Are there any edge cases or constraints to watch out for?
- Definition of Done: when is the task considered complete?

**Do not start coding until you have confirmation from the user.**

## Step 3 — Make a plan

After confirmation, present a checklist-style plan before coding:

```
[ ] Step 1 — ...
[ ] Step 2 — ...
[ ] Step 3 — ...
```

Wait for the user to approve the plan. If the user has feedback, revise the plan before proceeding.

## Step 4 — Implement

Execute according to the approved plan:

- Check off each step as you complete it
- If you encounter a blocker or discover additional scope → pause and notify the user before continuing

## Step 5 — Self-review

After implementation, review your work:

- Does the code follow project conventions? (see CLAUDE.md)
- Are there any linter errors?
- Does it meet the Definition of Done agreed upon in Step 2?

Give the user a brief summary of your review findings.

## Step 6 — Update Notion

When the user confirms the task is done, use the Notion MCP to update the task status:

- `Status`: **"Todo"** → **"Done"**

---

## Notes

- Always pause and ask the user if the scope changes mid-way
- If the user starts a conversation without specifying a task, ask: _"Do you want to fetch a task from Notion?"_
- The Notion MCP is already set up — use the `notionApi` tool to query/update
